    "summary": "### **Model Selection and the Large vs Small Trade-off** Over the last months, I‚Äôve moved from experimenting with chatbots to **engineering full generative-AI systems** ‚Äî tools that don‚Äôt just *talk* but *work*: they extract, validate, generate, and ...",
    "content": "\n\n\n### **Model Selection and the Large vs Small Trade-off**\n\nOver the last months, I‚Äôve moved from experimenting with chatbots to **engineering full generative-AI systems** ‚Äî tools that don‚Äôt just *talk* but *work*: they extract, validate, generate, and report.  \nThese posts are a reflection of what I‚Äôve learned along the way ‚Äî about models, prompts, APIs, and design choices that make LLMs practical in production.\n\nThis first part looks at **model selection** ‚Äî not in abstract benchmarks, but in the realities of *development* and *deployment*.\n\n---\n\n### **The Two Worlds: Large vs Small Models**\n\nI use **large models** for **development** ‚Äî when I need reasoning, creativity, or cross-domain insight.  \nThey are my partners in **architecture, design, coding, debugging, testing, and research**.  \nThey reason broadly, explain alternatives, and are forgiving when I haven‚Äôt defined a task precisely.\n\nBy contrast, I use **small models** for **deployment** ‚Äî where privacy, latency, and reproducibility matter.  \nOnce a workflow is clear and structured, a smaller instruction-tuned model executes it faster, cheaper, and often more reliably.\n\n---\n\n### **Why Larger Isn‚Äôt Always Better**\n\nA large model statistically produces *fewer errors a priori* ‚Äî its predictions are more consistent across unseen cases.  \nBut that same confidence can be deceptive: when it *does* err, it often does so with *high certainty* ‚Äî making the error less visible and harder to correct.  \nSmaller models may make more frequent mistakes, but their uncertainty can actually help expose flaws earlier, allowing *a posteriori* corrections and stronger validation loops.\n\nIn other words:  \n> **Large models are confident teachers. Small models are humble apprentices.**  \n> The trick is to know when to learn from one ‚Äî and when to rely on the other.\n\n---\n\n### **Outlook**\n\nIn the next posts, I‚Äôll cover:\n1. **System Prompts and Role Separation** ‚Äî how I structure `system_msg`, `user_msg`, and `style` layers for predictable output.  \n2. **Prompt APIs and Templates** ‚Äî how Jinja templates and JSON schemas define logic before generation.  \n3. **Client/Server and Deployment Models** ‚Äî running local vs remote inference, caching, and parametrisation.  \n\nTogether, these reflections form a blueprint for moving from *prompting* to *building*.\n\n---\n\n\n<p>Tags:\n{% for tag in page.tags %}\n  <a href=\"/tags/{{ tag | slugify }}/\">{{ tag }}</a>{% unless forloop.last %}, {% endunless %}\n{% endfor %}\n</p>\n",
